    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Specifically, tropical hardwood from trees of the genus Rhizophora. The wood from mangrove trees is primarily used for making charcoal or for poles in frame construction in houses. The term is also used in a general sense for wood from any tree having adaptations for living in water similar to those of genus Rhizophora.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000093795/Encyclopedia Britannica Online (2002-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000047822/MFA Conservation and Art Material Encyclopedia Online: CAMEO (2005-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Madera dura tropical utilizada a veces en construcción, como en postes de madera para la construcción de marcos en viviendas de África. </Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
